pullRequest.body:
Add lemmas about regular elements from commutative algebra.

---
<!-- The text above the `---` will become the commit message when your

To indicate co-authors, include lines at the bottom of the commit message
(that is, before the `---`) using the following format:

Co-authored-by: Author Name <author@email.com>

Any other comments you want to keep out of the PR commit should go
below the `---`, and placed outside this HTML comment, or else they
will be invisible to reviewers.

If this PR depends on other PRs, please list them below this comment,
using the following format:
- [ ] depends on: #abc [optional extra text]
- [ ] depends on: #xyz [optional extra text]
-->

The file `Algebra/Regular/SMul` is kept early in the algebraic hierarchy so there are plenty of basic lemmas about regular elements we can't state. This PR adds a file proving such things, like the fact that regularity is stable under tensoring with a flat module or a criterion for regularity on a quotient module in terms of the original module.

This is the last PR in the sequence of a PRs preparing for the development of regular sequences. I was trying to refactor that code more before creating a PR but I'm a bit stuck and I think it's a better idea to finish this part off and then submit a draft PR for feedback to get unstuck.

Pull request successfully merged into master.

Build succeeded:
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/9378167771/job/25820936758)
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/9378167771/job/25820936613)
I think you can use `nonZeroSMulDivisors` here?

I could, but I don't see the benefit of doing so. There's a benefit to stating things explicitly, changing it breaks at least one existing proof, and atm there's nowhere it's useful to have the set `nonZeroSMulDivisors`

> There's a benefit to stating things explicitly

I don't see that here though.

> there's nowhere it's useful to have the set `nonZeroSMulDivisors`

I think this is because `nonZeroSMulDivisors` is lacking API, but arguably some of the lemmas below (for example `isSMulRegular_of_range_eq_ker`) has nothing to do with the ring structure of `R` and is actually about `nonZeroSMulDivisors`.

Whether the existing API can help you is only half the story, the other half is whether your code could have improved the existing API.

I'll be satisfied if you add a separated lemma `IsSMulRegular M r ↔ r ∈ nonZeroSMulDivisors R M` though.
At least people searching for API around `nonZeroSMulDivisors` can find this page.
Are you planning to do this in this PR?
Ah good catch, I'll do a pass over my code for TODOs and fill them in
I think this holds for every `IsScalarTower`? Do we have this lemma?
Oh, very good point. I'll generalize to that case
I like this definition. Can we relax `r` to any `r : X` with `SMul X (Submodule R M)` so that `M ⧸ (I • ⊤ : Submodule R M)` can also be replaced by this?

I considered this. In a previous version of this code I had an smul action of List R on Submodule R M and it made some stuff a lot easier to write down. The downside to what you're suggesting is that R can no longer be inferred from r and M, so we need it as an explicit argument. This isn't a huge issue. The actually awkward thing is that we can't define things like `map` (ie assume the smul action is natural) or assume that smul'ing commutes with suprema. So it's a nice abbreviation and the theory of it works for elements/ideals/sets but (I think) there's no way to unify all those cases with existing typeclasses in mathlib. It didn't feel worth it to add the extra noise of an `R` parameter if all the lemmas in the namespace are about the special case `X = R`. We could add some typeclass support (I'm not entirely sure what this would look like) but I wasn't sure that was a good idea. Thoughts?

Fair enough. Let's keep it as is for now. 
Regarding the typeclass support: maybe we should have `HasQuotient M (Ideal R)` or `HasQuotient M r` so we can write `M ⧸ r` or `M ⧸ I`. Not sure if this is a good idea though.
Hmm, I'm not sure there's a way to set that up so that the two `HasQuotient R (Ideal R)` instances agree. I would love it if we could write `M ⧸ r` though
